[`Table.Column.title`][1] accepts a `ReactNode`, so you only need to render an `Ellipsis` component.

You should use `antd` built-in `Ellipsis`, for that use [`Typoghrapy` API][2].

**Note:** You should strain container&#39;s width so the ellipsing will work:

```
const COLUMN_STYLE = { width: 200 };
&lt;Typography.Text ellipsis={true} style={COLUMN_STYLE}&gt;
  A very long text
&lt;/Typography.Text&gt;
```

[![enter image description here][3]][3]

You can achieve the same effect with pure CSS, refer to [`text-overflow`.][4]

```
const dataSource = [
  {
    key: &#39;1&#39;,
    name: &#39;Mike&#39;
  },
  {
    key: &#39;2&#39;,
    name: &#39;John&#39;
  }
];

const COLUMN_STYLE = { width: 200 };

const customColumn = {
  title: (
    &lt;Typography.Text ellipsis={true} style={COLUMN_STYLE}&gt;
      My very-very-very long column-name My very-very-very long column-name My
      very-very-very long column-name
    &lt;/Typography.Text&gt;
  ),
  dataIndex: &#39;name&#39;,
  key: &#39;custom&#39;
};

const normalColumn = {
  title: &#39;My very-very-very long column-name&#39;,
  dataIndex: &#39;name&#39;
};

const TOTAL_COLUMNS = 6;

const columns = [...Array(TOTAL_COLUMNS).keys()].map(key =&gt; ({
  ...normalColumn,
  key
}));

const App = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Table dataSource={dataSource} columns={[customColumn, ...columns]} /&gt;
);
```

[![Edit Q-58287043-ColumnEllipsis](https://codesandbox.io/static/img/play-codesandbox.svg)](https://codesandbox.io/s/react-antd-styled-template-s27zk?fontsize=14)


  [1]: https://ant.design/components/table/#Column
  [2]: https://ant.design/components/typography/
  [3]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/spkY2.png
  [4]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/text-overflow

Since I am (yet) stuck with an old version of **Antd**, I went the inline-CSS way suggested by [Dennis Vash](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58290372/8330162). Within the `render()` function, I defined

```
var myColTitleStyle = {
            textOverflow: &#39;ellipsis&#39;,
            // overflow: &quot;hidden&quot;,
            whiteSpace: &#39;nowrap&#39;
};
```
Interestingly, I had to comment the parameter `overflow` out, although https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/text-overflow suggests that it is required for the property `text-overflow` to work. Also note the CamelWritingStyle of the css-properties within React.

Inside the component, the imports are
```js
import { Table } from &quot;antd&quot;;
const { Column, ColumnGroup } = Table;
```
The actual call of Antd&#39;s `Column` contains a `&lt;div&gt;` within the `title`, plus the inline-CSS:
```js
&lt;Column
   title={&lt;div style={myColTitleStyle}&gt;My long-long title&lt;/div&gt;}
   width=10
&gt;
```
Please also note that `textOverflow` will only work with absolute widths, which are dimensionless in React. It will *not* work when using percentage-widths.

